  <!-- Arktos generic structure origin story: modular, randomized, references survival after the Great War and rebuilding -->
  <IdeoStoryPatternDef>
    <defName>Arktos_StructureOriginStory</defName>
    <segments>
      <li>intro</li>
      <li>hardship</li>
      <li>response</li>
      <li>legacy</li>
    </segments>
    <rules>
      <include>
        <li>IdeoDescriptionGlobal</li>
      </include>
      <rulesStrings>
        <!-- allow zero or more optional hardship episodes -->
        <li>hardship(priority=-1)-></li>

        <!-- intro: a short establishing sentence about ancestors and the Great War -->
        <li>intro->Our ancestors were born into the ruins after the Great War, and learned to survive by cunning and shared labour.</li>
        <li>intro->After the Great War, the first generations faced hunger, storms and scavengers; they bound together to endure.</li>
        <li>intro->When the Great War ended, those who remained had to remake their habits and their homes from wreckage and memory.</li>

        <!-- hardship: variable episodes describing challenges -->
        <li>hardship(uses=1)->They battled the ruined machines and the roving bands that claimed the old cities.</li>
        <li>hardship(uses=1)->Plagues and cold nights took many, but surviving families learned to share what little they had.</li>
        <li>hardship(uses=1)->The land itself was poisoned in places; ancestors dug deep and learned where life stubbornly returned.</li>
        <li>hardship(uses=1)->At first there was no law; disputes were settled with fire and blade until councils formed to order life.</li>

        <!-- response: how ancestors rebuilt institutions, faith and craft -->
        <li>response->They taught their children to repair, to pray, to farm by moonlight, and to bind their fortunes together.</li>
        <li>response->They gathered tools and texts from the old world and mixed them with local rites until new customs grew.</li>
        <li>response->By pooling knowledge of seed, engine and story, they built settlements that could outlast another winter.</li>
        <li>response->Out of broken steel and whispered memory they formed new rites, new leaders, and rules that kept the peace.</li>

        <!-- legacy: tie to present and universal cultural origin line -->
        <li>legacy->This way — of craft, council and ritual — is how our people endured. It became the pattern that shaped our laws and our prayers.</li>
        <li>legacy->From those nights grew our ceremonies and our councils; what once was survival became the custom we follow today.</li>
        <li>legacy->Thus our children learn craft as liturgy, and the old stories teach us why our settlements stand where they do.</li>

        <!-- small variable pieces to spice sentences -->
        <li>place_descriptor->the broken plains</li>
        <li>place_descriptor->the ruined coasts</li>
        <li>place_descriptor->the ash-cloaked cities</li>
        <li>survivorType->engineers</li>
        <li>survivorType->farmers</li>
        <li>survivorType->scavengers</li>
      </rulesStrings>
    </rules>
  </IdeoStoryPatternDef>


